DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain encompasses core economic research on housing cost burdens, housing affordability
metrics, and rent-to-income ratios in Germany and Europe. Research focuses on measurement
approaches (ratio vs. residual income), burden distribution across income quintiles, trends
over time (particularly 1993-2024), and the relationship between housing expenditure and
income inequality. Key data sources include German Socio-Economic Panel (SOEP), EU-SILC,
EVS (Income and Consumption Survey), and administrative data. Major findings show that
housing expenditure dramatically amplifies income inequality trends, with burden rising
disproportionately for bottom income quintile while falling for top quintile. Germany shows
higher overburden rates (12.0%) than EU average (8.2%).

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
Provides baseline empirical evidence on housing burden patterns in Germany, essential for
testing Hypotheses 1, 2, and 4. Documents the income gradient in housing burden and provides
quantified evidence of how burden varies across income distribution.

KEY_DEBATES:
- Ratio approach (30/40% thresholds) vs. residual income approach
- Subjective vs. objective burden measurement
- Before-housing vs. after-housing income inequality
- Role of housing tenure (owner vs. renter) in burden distribution
====================================================================
